	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName> <date>15<hi rend="sup">th</hi> April 1851</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I beg as a <hi rend="underline">particular favor</hi> that you will<lb/> insert the annexed sketch of <persName>Dr E</persName> in the <date>May</date> Number of<lb/> the Occident&#44; placing it in some conspicuous place.  If you<lb/> <sic>canot</sic> get it in the <date>May</date> No oblige me by forwarding it to the<lb/> Editor of the Asmonean&#44; but I should prefer its being<lb/> in your valuable Journal.  <persName>Dr. E</persName> is opposed by&#44; several<lb/> of his congregation who are &#8220;tied&#8221; hand and foot to <persName>Poznanski</persName> &#38;<lb/> his infidel opinions.  <persName>Poznanski</persName> though that he could<lb/> mould<add>&#63;</add> <persName>Eckman</persName> to his will and make him the promulgator<lb/> of his infamous dogmas&#44; but the latter shrunk from the<lb/> contact&#44; and his boldly and fearlessly denounced him<lb/> and his infidelity.  As an impartial listener I have<lb/> given my views thinking they may benefit <persName>Dr. E</persName> whom<lb/> I believe to be a truly pious &#38; honest man&#44; his whole<lb/> aim &#38; object of life being to benefit his People and in<lb/> endeavoring to make them conform to the Holy Religion of their<lb/> Fathers.  I shall endeavour to procure some of his sermons<lb/> for publication in the Occident&#44; they are replete with<lb/> deep devotion&#44; lofty and sublime though&#44; and well<lb/> condensed arguments.  If you will forward me a Prospectus<lb/> of your Bible I can procure you some subscribers.  Since<lb/> my return from <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#44; a domestic affliction has<lb/> prevented me from conforming to the promise made when<lb/> I last saw you&#44; viz &#8220;that I would write often for the O.&#8221;<lb/>  I shall do so as often as I can.  I hope to hear<lb/> of your reinstatement as the spiritual head of the congregation &#8220;Mikveh<lb/> Israel.&#8221;  I have been defending you here against the vile<lb/> <sic>assersions</sic> of your enemies&#44; among whom you can enumerate<lb/> the <persName>Revd. Jacob Rosenfeld</persName> the applicant for your place who<lb/> I suppose has taken <del>up</del> umbrage at the remarks in a previous<lb/> number of the Occident.  The blow hit hard&#44; and<lb/> &#8220;the &#39;galled Jade <hi rend="underline">must</hi> wince.&#8221;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>He is beneath your contempt &#38; we shall soon get rid of<lb/> him.  So <sic>dont</sic> notice him any more.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I read your address on the presentation of the<lb/> silver with great pleasure and satisfaction.  Its<lb/> tone was happily conceived&#44; and must have touched even<lb/> the obdurate hearts of your detractors &#38; villifiers.</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Wshg<add>&#63;</add> you success &#38; health</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">I remain very truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Your friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Nathl Levine</persName></p>
				<p><persName>Mrs. L</persName> &#38; family desire their</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">kindest regards to you</p>
			
